o the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Shilston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from one or more of six places in Devon called  <i>Shilston(e)</i>, in Bishops Tawton, Chittlehampton, Drewsteignton, Exbourne, Modbury, and Throwleigh parishes."],"variants":[{"name":"Shilstone","meanings":["English:  see  Shilston  ."]},{"name":"Shilson","meanings":["English:  see  Shilston  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":6,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":15,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":60,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth De Shilston was born in 1322, in Modbury, Devon, England, her father, Sir William De Shilston, was 29 and her mother, Joan De Shilston, was 23. She married Gilbert De Wadham in 1343, in St Peter's Church, Knowstone, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 27 July 1412, in her hometown, at the age of 90, and was buried in Modbury, Devon, England."},"et":{"1322–27 July 1412":"1322–27. juuli 1412","1322–1412":"1322–1412","1320–1383":"1320–1383","1344–1412":"1344–1412","1348–Male":"1348–Surnud","1294–Male":"1294–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","Abt 1348":"umbes 1348","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1294":"1294","1337":"1337","1348":"1348","1412":"1412","1322":"1322","1344":"1344","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","27 July 1412":"27. juuli 1412","1328":"1328","Church of Saint George, Modbury, Devon, England":"Modbury, Devon, England","St Peter's Church, Knowstone, Devon, England":"St Peter's Church, Knowstone, Devon, England","Ilton, Somerset, England":"Ilton, Somerset, England","Shilston Manor, Modbury, Devon, England":"Modbury, Devon, England","Lustleigh, Devon, England, Unit